\b \cf0 String and Action Rows
\b0  - the following controls are on each row:\

\b +/- 
\b0 buttons - these are for adding or deleting a row of controls. When you add a row, the previous row's OSC string is copied. \

\b OSC string (sorted alphabetically)
\b0  - this string will be checked against the first item in any OSC messages received. If the string matches, the Actions will be triggered.\

\b on- off
\b0  - this turns the action on or off.\

\b trigger type
\b0  - the following choices are given: "
\i Always trigger
\i0 ", "
\i Trigger when arg = 1
\i0 ", and "
\i Trigger when arg = 0
\i0 ". The last 2 are useful for example with on/off button OSC messages. These options allow you to run  actions specifically when a value is turned ON or OFF - 1 meaning  "ON", and 0 meaning "OFF".\

\b use  args
\b0  - if switched on, this means that any arguments that come with the OSC string will be put into the value settings for the Action. \
The arguments can either be numbers or text strings.\
For example, if the Action selected was to set the frequency of a filter, or the BPM of a sequencer, then a number could be passed to set the value.\
If the Action selected had a checkbox to change settings (such as the Reverse checkbox in a Sample Player module), the OSC argument can be: (a) a text string with "ON" or "OFF",  or (b) a number with 1 meaning  "ON", and 0 meaning "OFF".\
If the Action selected had a popup to change settings (such as the type of Waveform  in a Wave Synth module), the OSC argument can be: (a) a text string of the popup value,  or (b) a number representing the index of the popup. (N.B. Index numbers start from 0, so 0 would be the index of the first item in the popup, 1 would be the index of the second item, 2 would be the index of the third item, etc.)\

\b from no
\b0  - this refers to the first argument that will be used for value settings. By default this will be 1, meaning the first OSC argument after the OSC string. Sometimes where OSC messages contain several arguments, higher values may be needed. For example, when using 2D sliders in TouchOSC iPad software, the X and Y values are sent as arguments 1 & 2. In this case, you might to create 2 rows, each with the same OSC string, but using different arguments numbers to run 2 different actions - for example controlling filter frequency and filter resonance.\

\b module
\b0  - selects which module will be used.\

\b action
\b0  - selects Action will be run out of all the possible Actions for the selected module.\

\b value settings
\b0  - depending on which Action is run, values can be set for the Action. \
For example, if the Action selected was to set the Frequency of a Waveform module, then a slider would be displayed for setting the frequency.\
